%%%%% TODO

[_] Define the minimal entity schema
  Include:
  - system identifier
  - opaque handle
  Decide which fields are fixed-width and always resident.
  Separate stable identity from cache slot location.

[_] Define the system protocol
  Systems interpret entity handles and own applicable operations.
  Keep non-system commands to a minimum.

[_] Define relation storage
  Pick the representation for child edges and high-fanout adjacency.
  Require lazy loading for very large child sets.

[_] Implement the working-set cache
  Add:
  - entity ID -> slot mapping
  - free-slot tracking
  - recency / eviction bookkeeping
  - eviction hooks for discard vs persist

[_] Define the common system frontend
  Specify how the rest of miur resolves a system, materializes entities, enumerates relations, and invokes ops.

[_] Implement the first concrete system
  Start with the ``miursys.localfs`` filesystem-backed system.
  Keep it small enough to validate the protocol before adding other domains.

[_] Define command and operation types
  Separate:
  - system-owned entity operations
  - the very small set of app-level commands outside those ops

[_] Build the core dispatch loop
  Centralize command handling, cache mutation, and refresh/invalidation flow.

[_] Build a minimal TUI
  One cursor, one list-oriented view, framed rendering, and command dispatch are enough for the first pass.

[_] Add preview workers
  Keep expensive preview generation out of the critical navigation path.

[_] Add persistence for unique data
  Start with annotations and durable overlays.
  Leave regeneratable graph fragments out of the persistence path.

[_] Define memory targets and tests
  Enforce the intended operating envelope:
  - typical working set under ~200 MiB
  - hard ceiling under ~8 GiB
  Add benchmarks for entity load, relation expansion, eviction, and refill.

[_] Audit legacy material
  Extract useful concepts from `legacy/` without inheriting obsolete implementation constraints.
